Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is now the 3rd health event that has led to meetings of the IHR Emergency Committee. The other 2 topics were influenza A pandemic (H1N1) 2009 (http://www.who.int/ihr/ihr_ec/en/) and MERS-CoV (http://www.who.int/ihr/ihr_ec_2013/en/). A necessary step for continuation of the goal of polio eradication.

In a discussion with a colleague last week, this moderator mentioned the probable need for a major coordinated international push to interrupt transmission of the wild poliovirus (WPV) in Asia, the Middle East, and in Africa simultaneously. Unfortunately, unlike smallpox where there were very few to none asymptomatic carriers of the smallpox virus, so silent transmission was not a significant issue, infection with poliovirus leads to paralytic disease for an average of 1 individual out of every 200 infected individuals (the actual range cited in the literature ranges from 1 in 50 to 1 in 1000), so that for every paralytic case that is identified through acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) surveillance, there are an average of 199 others who are infected with the WPV and are continuing to transmit the virus to susceptible contacts.

A good "case study", illustration of the challenges of asymptomatic infections is the situation in the Middle East -- a WPV genetically similar to those circulating in Pakistan was identified in sewage samples in Egypt in late 2012. No paralytic cases were identified associated with this WPV in Egypt. Several months later, sewage samples in Southern Israel were found to have WPVs, also genetically related to those circulating in Pakistan. Again, no paralytic cases were associated with these WPV isolates. During the course of 2013 and continuing into 2014, WPVs were identified in sewage samples travelling northward throughout Israel and in the Gaza strip and West Bank. Again, no paralytic cases were identified associated with these WPV isolates. In late 2013, paralytic cases were identified in Syria (which borders with northern Israel); the WPV associated with these cases in Syria was genetically related to those circulating in Pakistan. In early 2014, a paralytic case was identified in Iraq, again, a WPV was identified that was genetically related to those circulating in Pakistan. This 12 month history following WPV isolates not associated with clinical illnesses that were identified until the 1st paralytic cases were identified several countries distant from where the 1st isolates were found is a good example of how the WPV can travel silently and cover significant geographic territory before its presence is "announced" through a paralytic case appearing.

A question one asks is how much environmental sampling for WPVs is ongoing in African countries that have theoretically been WPV free (defined as no AFP cases from whom WPV has been identified). Another example of this type of silent circulation of the WPV was seen in September 2010 when there was a case of WPV associated paralytic disease in Uganda. The WPV identified was genetically related to a WPV that had been isolated from a paralytic case in the Turkana area of North West Kenya in February 2009. In that instance, the WPV had been silently circulating in the region for 19 months before it was identified in another paralytic case.

In reviewing the measures proposed by the IHR Emergency Committee, this is the 1st time that proof of recent vaccination with one of the childhood vaccines is being mandated for individuals coming from known "exporting" countries, and recommended for those coming from known infected countries. One wonders if a collateral action that polio free countries will take is to mandate vaccination at arrival for those travellers who do not have proof of recent vaccination against polio -- an action that countries used to take with respect to cholera vaccination and are still taking with respect to yellow fever vaccination.

One hopes that the international effort will be able to overcome the barriers to conducting vaccination activities in the areas of civil strife, and overcome the barriers of misinformation and anti-vaccination propaganda disseminated in these areas. - Mod.MPP]

